@model MusicGearTracker.Models.Instrument

@* 
The following form controls (fields) are based on BS docs.
Link: https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/forms/form-control/#example 

But in MVC, we should use Razor Tag Helpers so the form works with:
- Model Binding
- Validation
- Data Annotations
- Automatic value population (especially for Edit)

So, instead of Manual id Attributes, we should use "asp-for"

Tag Helpers in ASP.NET Core:
****************************
Tag Helpers enable server-side code to participate in creating and rendering HTML elements in Razor files.
Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/aspnet/core/mvc/views/tag-helpers/intro

Model Binding in ASP.NET Core:
******************************
Controllers and Razor pages work with data that comes from HTTP requests.
Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/aspnet/core/mvc/models/model-binding

However, you can still override the generated "id" attribute
if you want to target the element with custom JavaScript or CSS.

Be careful not to override the "name" attribute,
because ASP.NET Core MVC uses the "name" value for Model Binding.
Changing it can prevent the model from binding correctly.

We can still use JavaScript to target it easily: document.getElementById("Name")
because Razor already generated the id.

Notice also that In ASP.NET Core MVC, 
the value used in asp-for must match the C# model property name, which also follows PascalCase.

So we must use for example [asp-for="Name"] NOT [asp-for="name"] based on the original field/property in the Model

Why Name and not name?
**********************
Because asp-for references the C# model property, not an HTML attribute. 
The asp-for value must match the property name exactly.

Why It Uses PascalCase?
***********************
In Razor, asp-for is not a simple string.
It is a strongly typed expression referencing the model property.

HTML itself is case-insensitive, 
but Razor still requires the exact property name to correctly bind the model.

Example:
HTML: <input asp-for="Name" />

is interpreted by Razor roughly like: model => model.Name

So the framework is referencing the actual C# property.

What Happens If we Write name (lowercase)?
******************************************
We will get a compile-time error because the property does not exist.

Working with forms in ASP.NET Core MVC
Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/aspnet/core/mvc/views/working-with-forms
*@



@* 
    IMPORTANT NOTE ABOUT ID FIELD:
    ******************************

    We DO NOT include the Id field in the Create form:
        - The Id is the primary key
        - It is automatically generated by the database (auto-increment)
        - Users should NEVER enter or modify primary keys

    During Create:
    - The Id value is NOT sent from the form
    - The database generates it when saving the record

    During Edit:
    - We MUST send the Id back to the server
    - So the application knows which record to update

    Therefore:
    - Id field is included ONLY in Edit views (as a hidden field)
    - NOT in Create views

    Notice that if we include Id in Create:
        - The form sends an empty value ("")
        - ASP.NET Core fails to convert it to int
        - ModelState becomes invalid

    Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/models/model-binding
*@

@*
    NOTE To Review:
    ***************
    The value of "asp-for" must match the model property name exactly.
    Because C# is case-sensitive, the property must use PascalCase
    as defined in the model class.

    ASP.NET Core MVC then automatically generates the correct
    HTML "id" and "name" attributes required for Model Binding.

    Example:
        asp-for="Name" => correct
        asp-for="name" => compile-time error
*@

@* Name *@
<div class="mb-3">
    <label asp-for="Name" class="form-label"></label>
    <input asp-for="Name" type="text" class="form-control" placeholder="Instrument's name">
    <span asp-validation-for="Name" class="text-danger"></span>
</div>

@* Description *@
<div class="mb-3">
    <label asp-for="Description" class="form-label"></label>
    <textarea asp-for="Description" class="form-control" rows="3" placeholder="Instrument's specifications"></textarea>
    <span asp-validation-for="Description" class="text-danger"></span>
</div>

@* Price *@
<div class="mb-3">
    <label asp-for="Price" class="form-label"></label>
     @*
        We used type="number" to ensure valid numeric input. This helps:
            - Prevent invalid data entry (like enter text instead of number)
            - Improve user experience (numeric keyboard on mobile devices)
            - Reduce validation errors :-)

        The "step" attribute allows decimal values.

        Example:
            step="0.01" => allows values like 10.99
    *@
    <input asp-for="Price" type="number" step="0.01" class="form-control">
    <span asp-validation-for="Price" class="text-danger"></span>
</div>

@* 
NOTE: 
*****
"asp-validation-for" displays validation messages,
these validation messages are generated from Data Annotations defined in the model class

Because our model uses:
    [Required]
    public string Name { get; set; }

We should include validation:
    <span asp-validation-for="Name"></span>

Otherwise validation messages will not appear in the UI.
Link: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/mvc/models/validation?view=aspnetcore-10.0
*@

@* 
  Remember: 
  - asp-for already generates id and name automatically.
  - Manually overriding them can break model binding.

 Example:
 1) HTML:
    <input asp-for="Name">

 2) Becomes:
    <input type="text" id="Name" name="Name">

 This automatic mapping is part of the model binding system in ASP.NET Core MVC.

 Only override the "id" if absolutely necessary.
 Never override the "name" unless you fully understand
 how ASP.NET Core MVC model binding works.
*@